1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,360
 Dear everyone, our distinguished guests, faculty, students,

2
00:00:04,360 --> 00:00:08,160
 alumni, and brothers and sisters in Christ, good afternoon.

3
00:00:08,160 --> 00:00:11,920
 Welcome to China Graduate School of Theology.

4
00:00:11,920 --> 00:00:15,840
 The Josephine Soul Culture and Ethics Lecture Series this year

5
00:00:15,840 --> 00:00:20,840
 marks the beginning of our 50th anniversary celebration.

6
00:00:20,840 --> 00:00:24,760
 As CGST reaches the half centennial milestone,

7
00:00:24,760 --> 00:00:28,520
 we reflect on a journey marked by abundant grace

8
00:00:28,520 --> 00:00:31,280
 and faithfulness of our Lord.

9
00:00:31,280 --> 00:00:35,440
 This milestone is not just a celebration of our past,

10
00:00:35,440 --> 00:00:39,720
 but a testament to the steadfast mission of CGST

11
00:00:39,720 --> 00:00:42,960
 over five decades in serving the Church

12
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:46,400
 through theological education.

13
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:49,680
 Our Jubilee theme, [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

14
00:00:49,680 --> 00:00:53,920
 A Mission and Beyond, encapsulates our legacy

15
00:00:53,920 --> 00:00:57,280
 while looking toward the future.

16
00:00:57,280 --> 00:01:00,240
 In a world characterized by rapid change,

17
00:01:00,240 --> 00:01:02,160
 we recognize the challenges posed

18
00:01:02,160 --> 00:01:06,160
 by generational divides, cultural shifts,

19
00:01:06,160 --> 00:01:08,960
 and global migration.

20
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:13,200
 Through intergenerational, interdenominational,

21
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:17,280
 cross-culture, and cross-regional engagement,

22
00:01:17,280 --> 00:01:20,520
 we aim to explore the relevance of the Christian faith

23
00:01:20,520 --> 00:01:25,640
 and reimagine how to fulfill the mission of God today.

24
00:01:25,640 --> 00:01:30,680
 The Josephine Soul Culture and Ethics Lecture Series

25
00:01:30,680 --> 00:01:34,560
 began 40 years ago in 1985.

26
00:01:34,560 --> 00:01:37,320
 Over the years, the series covered issues

27
00:01:37,320 --> 00:01:40,680
 such as the contextualization of Christianity,

28
00:01:40,680 --> 00:01:45,040
 the reconstruction of Chinese culture, and ethics.

29
00:01:45,040 --> 00:01:48,680
 To align with our 50th anniversary celebration,

30
00:01:48,680 --> 00:01:51,160
 the theme of this year's lecture series

31
00:01:51,160 --> 00:01:54,680
 is cultural crossroads, navigating

32
00:01:54,680 --> 00:01:59,800
 the dynamics of intercultural interactions.

33
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:03,240
 We are honored to have four distinguished guests

34
00:02:03,240 --> 00:02:07,640
 from around the world to speak to us these two days.

35
00:02:07,640 --> 00:02:09,640
 So let us give them a warm welcome.

36
00:02:09,640 --> 00:02:10,560
 I will introduce them--

37
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:13,960
 [APPLAUSE]

38
00:02:15,400 --> 00:02:18,360
 I will introduce them in the order of appearance

39
00:02:18,360 --> 00:02:19,920
 today and tomorrow.

40
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:23,360
 Our first speaker is from Los Angeles, USA.

41
00:02:23,360 --> 00:02:25,320
 Actually, a city captures our attention

42
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:27,360
 these couple of weeks, right?

43
00:02:27,360 --> 00:02:30,160
 Dr. Daniel D. Lee, Associate Professor

44
00:02:30,160 --> 00:02:32,720
 of Theology and Asian American Studies,

45
00:02:32,720 --> 00:02:35,680
 Fuller Theological Seminary.

46
00:02:35,680 --> 00:02:38,000
 Our second speaker is from, well, actually,

47
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:41,480
 many places, including Hong Kong, Singapore, Asia,

48
00:02:41,480 --> 00:02:43,240
 and perhaps the whole world.

49
00:02:43,240 --> 00:02:49,560
 Dr. Patrick Fung, Global Ambassador of OMF International.

50
00:02:49,560 --> 00:02:52,320
 Our third speaker, well, now lives in Australia,

51
00:02:52,320 --> 00:02:54,400
 but he is also from the UK.

52
00:02:54,400 --> 00:02:58,000
 Dr. Daryl Jackson, Principal of Whitney College,

53
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:01,520
 University of Divinity in Melbourne.

54
00:03:01,520 --> 00:03:04,760
 Finally, our fourth speaker is from the other side of Asia,

55
00:03:04,760 --> 00:03:06,160
 Israel.

56
00:03:06,160 --> 00:03:10,880
 Dr. Rula Mansour, Founder and Director of the Nazareth Center

57
00:03:10,880 --> 00:03:13,600
 for Peace Studies.

58
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:15,480
 Our speakers will delve into topics

59
00:03:15,480 --> 00:03:19,560
 such as identity, leadership, diaspora, and peace

60
00:03:19,560 --> 00:03:21,760
 and reconciliation.

61
00:03:21,760 --> 00:03:25,280
 It is our heartfelt prayer that this lecture series

62
00:03:25,280 --> 00:03:31,280
 and the entire Jubilee year will inspire fresh insights,

63
00:03:31,280 --> 00:03:34,480
 deepen our understanding, and spark new ways

64
00:03:34,480 --> 00:03:36,600
 of serving God together.

65
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:40,560
 So thank you for joining us in this significant celebration.

66
00:03:40,560 --> 00:03:44,480
 And I look forward to the enriching discussions ahead.

67
00:03:44,480 --> 00:03:45,480
 Thank you.

68
00:03:45,480 --> 00:03:48,440
 [APPLAUSE]

69
00:03:48,440 --> 00:03:55,400
 Good afternoon, everyone.

70
00:03:55,400 --> 00:03:57,920
 I'm Cherry Chen, Assistant Professor

71
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:02,840
 in Theological Studies at CGST, the host of today.

72
00:04:02,840 --> 00:04:05,840
 Welcome again to the first section of the Josephine So

73
00:04:05,840 --> 00:04:07,360
 Lecture Series.

74
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:09,480
 It is truly a joy to see all of you

75
00:04:09,480 --> 00:04:13,400
 here as we embark on this special journey together,

76
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:16,800
 celebrating the rich intersection of culture,

77
00:04:16,800 --> 00:04:19,320
 theology, and ethics.

78
00:04:19,320 --> 00:04:22,040
 We are deeply honored to have Dr. Daniel D.

79
00:04:22,040 --> 00:04:26,200
 Lee as our first speaker of this series.

80
00:04:26,200 --> 00:04:30,640
 Today, he will introduce us to a fascinating topic,

81
00:04:30,640 --> 00:04:35,560
 contextual paradox, non-essentialist identity,

82
00:04:35,560 --> 00:04:38,200
 divine encounter, and the dangers

83
00:04:38,200 --> 00:04:41,400
 of theological contextuality.

84
00:04:41,400 --> 00:04:45,080
 Dr. Lee wears many hats with distinction.

85
00:04:45,080 --> 00:04:49,080
 He is the academic dean of the Center of Asian-American

86
00:04:49,080 --> 00:04:53,160
 Theology and Ministry and an associate professor

87
00:04:53,160 --> 00:04:55,520
 of theology and Asian-American studies

88
00:04:55,520 --> 00:04:58,400
 at Thule Theological Seminary.

89
00:04:58,400 --> 00:05:00,480
 But that's not all.

90
00:05:00,480 --> 00:05:05,240
 He is also a prolific author whose work continues

91
00:05:05,240 --> 00:05:09,400
 to influence and shape the global theological landscape.

92
00:05:09,400 --> 00:05:12,200
 Some of his notable contributions

93
00:05:12,200 --> 00:05:15,600
 include Doing Asian-American Theology,

94
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:18,960
 a Contextual Framework for Faith and Practice,

95
00:05:18,960 --> 00:05:22,720
 Double Particularity, Calebot, Contextuality,

96
00:05:22,720 --> 00:05:27,360
 and Asian-American Theology, and The Theologies

97
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:32,600
 of Asian-Americans and Pacific Peoples, a reader, 1976.

98
00:05:32,600 --> 00:05:36,920
 Dr. Lee's research focuses on the reformed tradition

99
00:05:36,920 --> 00:05:38,920
 and contextual theologies.

100
00:05:38,920 --> 00:05:43,640
 And he brings with him not only academic expertise,

101
00:05:43,640 --> 00:05:47,040
 but also broad ministry experience.

102
00:05:47,040 --> 00:05:50,320
 His work challenges us to think critically

103
00:05:50,320 --> 00:05:53,960
 about the intersection of theology, identity,

104
00:05:53,960 --> 00:05:55,320
 and culture.

105
00:05:55,320 --> 00:06:00,280
 And I believe we are in for an intellectually stimulating

106
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:01,880
 section.

107
00:06:01,880 --> 00:06:06,360
 Following Dr. Lee's lecture, we will have our response

108
00:06:06,360 --> 00:06:10,960
 delivered by Dr. Daniel Lee of CGST.

109
00:06:10,960 --> 00:06:14,400
 Yes, to Dr. Daniel Lee today.

110
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:17,840
 Don't worry, we will keep things really clear.

111
00:06:17,840 --> 00:06:22,440
 Dr. Lee of CGST is the Eleanor and Wayne Shill Professor

112
00:06:22,440 --> 00:06:26,240
 of Theological Studies and has been faithfully serving

113
00:06:26,240 --> 00:06:29,480
 at CGST since 2005.

114
00:06:29,480 --> 00:06:33,240
 With his deep roots in the Presbyterian Church,

115
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:36,200
 Dr. Lee is passionate about coordinating

116
00:06:36,200 --> 00:06:40,760
 theological reflection with the contemporary challenges faced

117
00:06:40,760 --> 00:06:42,800
 by Christians today.

118
00:06:42,800 --> 00:06:47,520
 His vision is to achieve the rich resources of Reformation

119
00:06:47,520 --> 00:06:50,280
 theology and make them accessible

120
00:06:50,280 --> 00:06:52,400
 for the modern church.

121
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:55,600
 His book, The Theology of the Holy Spirit

122
00:06:55,600 --> 00:07:00,560
 as Born in Calvin's Fort, is a testament to this vision.

123
00:07:00,560 --> 00:07:05,680
 Now, without further ado, let us warmly welcome Dr. Daniel D.

124
00:07:05,680 --> 00:07:07,360
 Lee to deliver his lecture.

125
00:07:07,360 --> 00:07:10,760
 [APPLAUSE]

126
00:07:10,760 --> 00:07:21,000
 You know, back at Fuller, there's so many Daniel Lees

127
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:23,520
 that I had to put Daniel D. Lee.

128
00:07:23,520 --> 00:07:26,720
 But it turns out that no matter where I go,

129
00:07:26,720 --> 00:07:28,520
 multiple Daniel Lees follow me.

130
00:07:28,520 --> 00:07:29,020
 So--

131
00:07:29,020 --> 00:07:32,480
 [LAUGHTER]

132
00:07:32,480 --> 00:07:35,040
 All right.

133
00:07:35,040 --> 00:07:37,440
 Let me begin with--

134
00:07:37,440 --> 00:07:39,920
 here we go.

135
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:42,480
 Let me begin with a word of appreciation for President Wong

136
00:07:42,480 --> 00:07:43,360
 for this invitation.

137
00:07:43,360 --> 00:07:47,120
 What a joy to be part of this Josephine Sill

138
00:07:47,120 --> 00:07:49,280
 Lectureship on Culture and Ethics

139
00:07:49,280 --> 00:07:54,440
 on this special occasion of celebrating China Graduate

140
00:07:54,440 --> 00:07:58,480
 School of Theology's 50 years of faithful service.

141
00:07:58,480 --> 00:08:03,360
 As I pondered upon the four themes of 50 years anniversary

142
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:04,920
 celebration--

143
00:08:04,920 --> 00:08:07,840
 cross-generational, cross-denominational,

144
00:08:07,840 --> 00:08:10,160
 cross-cultural, and cross-regional--

145
00:08:10,160 --> 00:08:11,600
 I thought about organizing my talk

146
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:17,640
 around the various paradoxes of theological contextuality.

147
00:08:17,640 --> 00:08:24,480
 Now, before I continue to do that,

148
00:08:24,480 --> 00:08:27,400
 I want to share a bit of my work and just my context.

149
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:29,880
 So I'm the founding academic dean

150
00:08:29,880 --> 00:08:32,240
 for Fuller Seminary's Center for Asian-American Theology

151
00:08:32,240 --> 00:08:35,760
 and Ministry, otherwise known as the Asian-American Center.

152
00:08:35,760 --> 00:08:38,960
 Our mission is to equip, resource, and research

153
00:08:38,960 --> 00:08:41,040
 the Asian-American church.

154
00:08:41,040 --> 00:08:43,160
 And that basically means we train and support

155
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:46,480
 Asian-American Christian leaders.

156
00:08:46,480 --> 00:08:50,320
 And this sounds really odd for non-Asian-Americans,

157
00:08:50,320 --> 00:08:53,920
 because the word Asian is nonsense.

158
00:08:53,920 --> 00:08:55,080
 Everybody's Asian, right?

159
00:08:55,080 --> 00:08:58,080
 But in the US, it actually means something particular, right?

160
00:08:58,080 --> 00:09:02,800
 So we have within our center East Asian-Americans,

161
00:09:02,800 --> 00:09:07,360
 Southeast Asian-Americans, Southeast Asian-Americans,

162
00:09:07,360 --> 00:09:09,880
 multiracial Asian-Americans, people

163
00:09:09,880 --> 00:09:12,920
 who are quarter Chinese-American,

164
00:09:12,920 --> 00:09:15,000
 because it matters for them somehow, right?

165
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:16,840
 We have a lot of adoptees.

166
00:09:16,840 --> 00:09:19,760
 And somehow, all these different people

167
00:09:19,760 --> 00:09:22,080
 are under this umbrella called Asian-America.

168
00:09:22,080 --> 00:09:25,200
 And this identity means something, right?

169
00:09:25,200 --> 00:09:26,400
 And the question is--

170
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:30,480
 and of course, even though you might have cousins who

171
00:09:30,480 --> 00:09:32,920
 are in Canada or Australia, you think

172
00:09:32,920 --> 00:09:35,720
 about generational conflict between first and second

173
00:09:35,720 --> 00:09:36,600
 generation.

174
00:09:36,600 --> 00:09:38,640
 But in the US, there's actually 170 years

175
00:09:38,640 --> 00:09:40,400
 of Asian-American history.

176
00:09:40,400 --> 00:09:41,560
 This is a long history, right?

177
00:09:41,560 --> 00:09:44,720
 So I regularly interact with fifth generation

178
00:09:44,720 --> 00:09:49,120
 Japanese-American and fourth generation Chinese-Americans.

179
00:09:49,120 --> 00:09:50,620
 So we talk about that in addressing

180
00:09:50,620 --> 00:09:52,440
 the spiritual and psychological concerns,

181
00:09:52,440 --> 00:09:55,960
 because Fuller has a school of psychology as well.

182
00:09:55,960 --> 00:09:57,680
 And we train Asian-American leaders,

183
00:09:57,680 --> 00:09:59,880
 whatever their context may be, because some of them,

184
00:09:59,880 --> 00:10:02,080
 they don't actually serve in Asian-American ministry

185
00:10:02,080 --> 00:10:02,880
 context.

186
00:10:02,880 --> 00:10:04,440
 They serve in multi-ethnic context.

187
00:10:04,440 --> 00:10:06,520
 They might do all kind of different things.

188
00:10:06,520 --> 00:10:10,480
 Or we might train people who work with Asian-Americans

189
00:10:10,480 --> 00:10:14,280
 to understand who these people are, right?

190
00:10:14,280 --> 00:10:15,520
 It's very broad.

191
00:10:15,520 --> 00:10:18,480
 So the question is, what do these people share together?

192
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:20,800
 When you have an Indian-American,

193
00:10:20,800 --> 00:10:25,040
 what do they really share with a Korean-American?

194
00:10:25,040 --> 00:10:26,920
 What does that mean?

195
00:10:26,920 --> 00:10:28,800
 So that's basically been the struggle,

196
00:10:28,800 --> 00:10:32,000
 because apparently in the US, all the white people

197
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:33,840
 lump us together.

198
00:10:33,840 --> 00:10:36,760
 And that actually became something, right?

199
00:10:36,760 --> 00:10:38,600
 So one of my theological goals have

200
00:10:38,600 --> 00:10:44,760
 been to help Asian-American individuals, as well

201
00:10:44,760 --> 00:10:48,480
 as communities, know who they are,

202
00:10:48,480 --> 00:10:52,280
 and also to bring their whole selves into God's presence

203
00:10:52,280 --> 00:10:56,040
 for healing, for transformation, and for calling.

204
00:10:56,040 --> 00:10:57,560
 That's basically what I do.

205
00:10:57,560 --> 00:11:04,320
 And that mission, this concern, is what is filling my mind.

206
00:11:04,320 --> 00:11:06,920
 And that's the perspective which I'm giving this lecture.

207
00:11:07,520 --> 00:11:08,920
 OK?

208
00:11:08,920 --> 00:11:10,360
 So without that context, it would

209
00:11:10,360 --> 00:11:11,720
 be very difficult to say, why am I

210
00:11:11,720 --> 00:11:13,520
 thinking about these certain things, right?

211
00:11:13,520 --> 00:11:19,080
 Let me make two clarifications before I continue on.

212
00:11:19,080 --> 00:11:22,200
 This is like my prologama.

213
00:11:22,200 --> 00:11:24,800
 One is about paradox, and the other one

214
00:11:24,800 --> 00:11:26,400
 is about contextuality.

215
00:11:26,400 --> 00:11:28,040
 First clarification.

216
00:11:28,040 --> 00:11:29,600
 I draw my understanding of paradox

217
00:11:29,600 --> 00:11:32,760
 from Martin Luther's Theology of the Cross, or Theological

218
00:11:32,760 --> 00:11:34,520
 Crucifixion.

219
00:11:34,520 --> 00:11:38,920
 In his Heidelberg Dispensation from 1518,

220
00:11:38,920 --> 00:11:43,280
 he talks about how the gospel message is paradoxical.

221
00:11:43,280 --> 00:11:43,780
 Why?

222
00:11:43,780 --> 00:11:48,320
 Because a savior who dies saves us, which, as you know,

223
00:11:48,320 --> 00:11:50,480
 is nonsense, right?

224
00:11:50,480 --> 00:11:52,600
 Or for you to be great in the kingdom,

225
00:11:52,600 --> 00:11:55,080
 you have to become humble.

226
00:11:55,080 --> 00:11:57,200
 So much of the gospel is paradoxical.

227
00:11:57,200 --> 00:11:58,640
 It's not really logical.

228
00:11:58,640 --> 00:12:01,480
 It's a paradoxical logic.

229
00:12:01,480 --> 00:12:04,000
 It turns out that so much of the gospel

230
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:06,720
 and how we think about who our God is,

231
00:12:06,720 --> 00:12:11,640
 it's talking about a God who justifies the ungodly, which

232
00:12:11,640 --> 00:12:13,760
 is the doctrine of justification,

233
00:12:13,760 --> 00:12:19,000
 or God who paradoxically creates the world out of nothing,

234
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:20,680
 or who raises the dead.

235
00:12:20,680 --> 00:12:22,560
 I mean, by definition, dead people are dead.

236
00:12:22,560 --> 00:12:24,680
 You don't raise them.

237
00:12:24,680 --> 00:12:28,080
 So it's not about a logical conclusion about who God is.

238
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:30,280
 It's about a paradoxical revelation

239
00:12:30,280 --> 00:12:32,440
 of what this God is like.

240
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:35,120
 Not just any God, but this particular God.

241
00:12:35,120 --> 00:12:36,760
 This is how this God works.

242
00:12:36,760 --> 00:12:39,720
 And we should think along in that sense.

243
00:12:39,720 --> 00:12:43,160
 I always tell my students, we're not theists.

244
00:12:43,160 --> 00:12:45,320
 Theism doesn't really help us that much.

245
00:12:45,320 --> 00:12:47,280
 It's not the fact that God exists.

246
00:12:47,280 --> 00:12:50,440
 It's that this particular God exists.

247
00:12:50,440 --> 00:12:51,520
 It's a huge difference.

248
00:12:51,520 --> 00:12:53,680
 You can't just jump from here, theism,

249
00:12:53,680 --> 00:12:55,760
 just to the Christian God.

250
00:12:55,760 --> 00:12:57,320
 So that's basically what I'm thinking

251
00:12:57,320 --> 00:12:58,640
 about in terms of paradox.

252
00:12:58,640 --> 00:13:01,560
 That things, when you think theologically,

253
00:13:01,560 --> 00:13:03,400
 you would think paradoxically.

254
00:13:03,400 --> 00:13:05,080
 And you will know how the gospel works.

255
00:13:05,080 --> 00:13:10,720
 Sometimes I get this question, well,

256
00:13:10,720 --> 00:13:13,480
 you're an Asian-American theologian.

257
00:13:13,480 --> 00:13:17,440
 Isn't Martin Luther a medieval German theologian?

258
00:13:17,440 --> 00:13:22,760
 So should you really be using a German theologian?

259
00:13:22,760 --> 00:13:25,280
 I say, this is what I find interesting.

260
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:28,880
 When you study Luther, what he's trying to do

261
00:13:28,880 --> 00:13:31,560
 is critique his context.

262
00:13:31,560 --> 00:13:35,160
 He knows that so much of the theology of his time

263
00:13:35,160 --> 00:13:38,120
 was taken up by Western philosophical tradition,

264
00:13:38,120 --> 00:13:39,520
 Aristotelian ethics.

265
00:13:39,520 --> 00:13:42,320
 And he said the gospel isn't that.

266
00:13:42,320 --> 00:13:44,760
 So in some sense, I find that interesting

267
00:13:44,760 --> 00:13:47,040
 from my perspective as an Asian-American,

268
00:13:47,040 --> 00:13:50,920
 as I try to critique my white American education,

269
00:13:50,920 --> 00:13:52,680
 and the gospel is not that.

270
00:13:52,680 --> 00:13:54,720
 But it's not really my Asian heritage either.

271
00:13:54,720 --> 00:13:56,720
 The gospel is not that either.

272
00:13:56,720 --> 00:13:58,480
 There's going to be a conversion no matter

273
00:13:58,480 --> 00:13:59,800
 where you're coming from.

274
00:13:59,800 --> 00:14:02,840
 That conversion experience of what Luther talks about,

275
00:14:02,840 --> 00:14:06,680
 I find it helpful for my purposes.

276
00:14:06,680 --> 00:14:08,560
 So that's the paradoxical reasoning.

277
00:14:08,560 --> 00:14:19,000
 The second point is this idea of theological contextuality

278
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:22,440
 as opposed to contextual theology.

279
00:14:22,440 --> 00:14:28,160
 I generally don't like the term contextual theology.

280
00:14:28,160 --> 00:14:29,160
 This is the reason why.

281
00:14:29,160 --> 00:14:35,080
 When people talk about contextual theology,

282
00:14:35,080 --> 00:14:40,680
 this label, it's usually used to label people

283
00:14:40,680 --> 00:14:44,040
 who are not normal theologians.

284
00:14:44,040 --> 00:14:45,520
 You know what I'm saying, right?

285
00:14:45,520 --> 00:14:48,280
 Oh, Calvin, he's a normal theologian.

286
00:14:48,280 --> 00:14:53,040
 But somebody like me, maybe I don't look normal,

287
00:14:53,040 --> 00:14:54,560
 especially in the US.

288
00:14:54,560 --> 00:14:58,960
 So non-normal theologians are considered contextual,

289
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:02,840
 the majority world, whatever that is.

290
00:15:02,840 --> 00:15:05,920
 So in a sense, this contextual ends up

291
00:15:05,920 --> 00:15:08,560
 being a way in which you separate

292
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:12,040
 the non-Western majority world, the non-white theology,

293
00:15:12,040 --> 00:15:15,320
 from the mainstream just theology,

294
00:15:15,320 --> 00:15:17,480
 just biblical theology.

295
00:15:17,480 --> 00:15:19,760
 What am I reading, the Buddhist sutras?

296
00:15:19,760 --> 00:15:21,480
 I'm reading the Bible, too.

297
00:15:21,480 --> 00:15:23,960
 Why am I not biblical theologian?

298
00:15:23,960 --> 00:15:25,840
 In that sense, I think the question

299
00:15:25,840 --> 00:15:28,040
 of contextual theology ends up being

300
00:15:28,040 --> 00:15:32,040
 a politics of who you label.

301
00:15:32,040 --> 00:15:35,080
 Now, what's weird is that if you ask anybody in the US,

302
00:15:35,080 --> 00:15:38,760
 at least, they'll say, of course I'm contextual.

303
00:15:38,760 --> 00:15:40,920
 And I say, well, what does that mean?

304
00:15:40,920 --> 00:15:42,120
 What does that mean?

305
00:15:42,120 --> 00:15:43,720
 But the common sense is that when

306
00:15:43,720 --> 00:15:46,760
 we think about contextual theology or contextualization,

307
00:15:46,760 --> 00:15:49,120
 there's this universal gospel.

308
00:15:49,120 --> 00:15:51,920
 And of course, if you're white or European,

309
00:15:51,920 --> 00:15:54,200
 they have it already.

310
00:15:54,200 --> 00:15:56,600
 But oh, these poor people in Hong Kong,

311
00:15:56,600 --> 00:15:59,320
 they have to contextualize.

312
00:15:59,320 --> 00:16:02,440
 And I say, oh, this is a big problem.

313
00:16:02,440 --> 00:16:07,360
 In that sense, then we have a problem how we label things

314
00:16:07,360 --> 00:16:10,360
 as contextual, right?

315
00:16:10,360 --> 00:16:12,960
 One of my favorite writers, purely surprising winner,

316
00:16:12,960 --> 00:16:16,280
 novelist Viet Nguyen, he talks about-- he

317
00:16:16,280 --> 00:16:20,360
 rejects the label of being the great Vietnamese-American

318
00:16:20,360 --> 00:16:22,080
 writer.

319
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:24,560
 People are like, oh, you know, New York Times,

320
00:16:24,560 --> 00:16:27,280
 the great Vietnamese-American writer.

321
00:16:27,280 --> 00:16:31,600
 And he says, well, do you call F. Scott Fitzgerald

322
00:16:31,600 --> 00:16:35,000
 the great white American writer?

323
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:35,960
 Right?

324
00:16:35,960 --> 00:16:42,480
 He basically says, adjective for all or adject for none.

325
00:16:42,480 --> 00:16:46,720
 Either we're all just writers, or I

326
00:16:46,720 --> 00:16:48,440
 am Vietnamese-American writer, and he's

327
00:16:48,440 --> 00:16:50,560
 a white American writer, right?

328
00:16:50,560 --> 00:16:56,360
 Because labels are being used to tell people you're not normal.

329
00:16:56,360 --> 00:16:58,760
 And then there is such thing as normal.

330
00:16:58,760 --> 00:17:01,000
 And that's the problem.

331
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:03,880
 Either label nothing because the labeling itself

332
00:17:03,880 --> 00:17:05,760
 is being used to marginalize.

333
00:17:05,760 --> 00:17:08,760
 So in that sense, I'm just a theologian.

334
00:17:08,760 --> 00:17:10,880
 But theoretically, it's possible.

335
00:17:10,880 --> 00:17:13,960
 But this idea of labeling nothing

336
00:17:13,960 --> 00:17:15,240
 still ends up being problematic.

337
00:17:15,240 --> 00:17:18,240
 Because for all the white European theologians,

338
00:17:18,240 --> 00:17:20,360
 let's just be business as usual.

339
00:17:20,360 --> 00:17:22,680
 They'll still label me anyways.

340
00:17:22,680 --> 00:17:28,120
 So my perspective is, well, you can start labeling everything

341
00:17:28,120 --> 00:17:32,160
 and expose all the hidden assumptions.

342
00:17:32,160 --> 00:17:36,000
 Locate yourself as a theologian and your work explicitly.

343
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:40,640
 Make this labeling itself your theological and ethical

344
00:17:40,640 --> 00:17:44,200
 responsibility.

345
00:17:44,200 --> 00:17:48,600
 So in that sense, I would be an Asian-American theologian.

346
00:17:48,600 --> 00:17:53,000
 Either way, you can use the word contextual in that sense.

347
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:53,920
 Everybody's contextual.

348
00:17:53,920 --> 00:17:56,720
 But what I really want to push for

349
00:17:56,720 --> 00:18:00,960
 is this idea of contextuality that everybody

350
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:03,000
 is interacting with.

351
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:04,960
 What does this mean?

352
00:18:04,960 --> 00:18:07,640
 If somebody just says, well, of course I'm contextual.

353
00:18:07,640 --> 00:18:13,640
 I think I was talking to Hauras, and he was visiting Fuller.

354
00:18:13,640 --> 00:18:15,240
 And I asked him, what does he mean?

355
00:18:15,240 --> 00:18:16,820
 He goes, oh, of course I'm contextual.

356
00:18:16,820 --> 00:18:18,800
 He just moved on.

357
00:18:18,800 --> 00:18:20,480
 And I said, that means nothing.

358
00:18:20,480 --> 00:18:23,360
 It literally is meaningless if you get to say it that way.

359
00:18:23,360 --> 00:18:25,800
 Because for me, I have to describe this.

360
00:18:25,800 --> 00:18:28,200
 It has to mean something in particular.

361
00:18:28,200 --> 00:18:30,280
 Because this idea of theological contextuality

362
00:18:30,280 --> 00:18:33,120
 has to be developed, we're not there yet.

363
00:18:33,120 --> 00:18:34,520
 We have to unpack this thing.

364
00:18:34,520 --> 00:18:35,960
 But if you can talk about it, you

365
00:18:35,960 --> 00:18:39,400
 can talk about how are you dealing with contextuality?

366
00:18:39,400 --> 00:18:40,520
 How am I dealing with it?

367
00:18:40,520 --> 00:18:42,840
 How are we dealing with it?

368
00:18:42,840 --> 00:18:45,320
 And especially the ones that don't

369
00:18:45,320 --> 00:18:48,040
 talk about the fact that they're contextual, that don't

370
00:18:48,040 --> 00:18:49,900
 understand they're contextual, that

371
00:18:49,900 --> 00:18:52,520
 is one of the most important points.

372
00:18:52,520 --> 00:18:54,760
 How are you dealing with contextuality?

373
00:18:54,760 --> 00:18:58,240
 So that's what I'm talking about in terms of contextuality.

374
00:18:58,240 --> 00:18:59,840
 So enough of the polygam.

375
00:19:02,760 --> 00:19:07,640
 Here is the outline of my lecture.

376
00:19:07,640 --> 00:19:11,440
 And I would address three topics.

377
00:19:11,440 --> 00:19:16,880
 And with three topics, I'll talk about the conflicting crisis

378
00:19:16,880 --> 00:19:20,160
 and what I think is a paradoxical intervention

379
00:19:20,160 --> 00:19:21,360
 to fix the problem.

380
00:19:21,360 --> 00:19:23,560
 Where's the gospel intervention?

381
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:26,000
 It's actually a lot more complicated than you realize.

382
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:27,480
 It is not straightforward.

383
00:19:31,480 --> 00:19:33,760
 First topic is the challenge of defining

384
00:19:33,760 --> 00:19:37,040
 a context or an identity.

385
00:19:37,040 --> 00:19:39,800
 And you'll see why I think it's very, very problematic.

386
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:41,240
 And I'll tell you why.

387
00:19:41,240 --> 00:19:48,880
 My journey of becoming an Asian-American theologian was--

388
00:19:48,880 --> 00:19:51,800
 I didn't like the idea of Asian-American theology.

389
00:19:51,800 --> 00:19:54,240
 So God kind of like--

390
00:19:54,240 --> 00:19:56,480
 even the fact that I'm here lecturing

391
00:19:56,480 --> 00:19:59,480
 about Asian-American, I just find it very ironic.

392
00:19:59,480 --> 00:20:01,280
 Because I just didn't want to do it.

393
00:20:01,280 --> 00:20:03,400
 God kind of like dragged me kicking and screaming.

394
00:20:03,400 --> 00:20:05,800
 And I'll talk about why.

395
00:20:05,800 --> 00:20:08,760
 Second one's about addressing the very basis

396
00:20:08,760 --> 00:20:10,520
 of theological contextuality.

397
00:20:10,520 --> 00:20:15,800
 That its very foundation is in a doctrine of God.

398
00:20:15,800 --> 00:20:19,640
 And the last one is about the dangers of contextuality.

399
00:20:19,640 --> 00:20:21,400
 Because I always get questions about that.

400
00:20:21,400 --> 00:20:26,160
 So hopefully I can kind of feel those concerns.

401
00:20:26,160 --> 00:20:29,320
 Defining the context.

402
00:20:29,320 --> 00:20:32,480
 I wonder if you know who this is.

403
00:20:32,480 --> 00:20:36,440
 I heard gospel coalitions here and everywhere else as well.

404
00:20:36,440 --> 00:20:38,400
 It's all around the world.

405
00:20:38,400 --> 00:20:40,320
 This is Tim Keller, famous New York--

406
00:20:40,320 --> 00:20:42,240
 he's late, Tim Keller.

407
00:20:42,240 --> 00:20:43,480
 Very influential in my life.

408
00:20:43,480 --> 00:20:45,920
 And I think there was a joke that--

409
00:20:45,920 --> 00:20:46,920
 well, it was not a joke.

410
00:20:46,920 --> 00:20:49,240
 Because his church, Vidiemur in New York City,

411
00:20:49,240 --> 00:20:53,160
 was the biggest Asian-American church in the East Coast.

412
00:20:53,160 --> 00:20:55,720
 Because half of his church was Asian-American.

413
00:20:55,720 --> 00:20:57,840
 But all the staff was white.

414
00:20:57,840 --> 00:21:00,800
 So really, really influential.

415
00:21:00,800 --> 00:21:04,000
 So think about it.

416
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:05,760
 The first topic is about the complications

417
00:21:05,760 --> 00:21:09,040
 of defining a context, and correspondingly,

418
00:21:09,040 --> 00:21:11,440
 what it means to have an identity as well.

419
00:21:11,440 --> 00:21:14,800
 And identity and context are intertwined.

420
00:21:14,800 --> 00:21:16,160
 There's a thing called Hong Kong.

421
00:21:16,160 --> 00:21:19,080
 There are people called Hong Kongers.

422
00:21:19,080 --> 00:21:21,480
 So we'll talk about that a little bit later.

423
00:21:21,480 --> 00:21:24,360
 And now because it's deeply rooted in individualism,

424
00:21:24,360 --> 00:21:27,440
 in mainstream American society, you generally

425
00:21:27,440 --> 00:21:30,480
 see it as an individual, with your own personality,

426
00:21:30,480 --> 00:21:31,920
 with your values.

427
00:21:31,920 --> 00:21:36,000
 And this idea is there in theology as well.

428
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:37,000
 Or even like ministry.

429
00:21:37,000 --> 00:21:39,320
 You might read a Tim Keller book,

430
00:21:39,320 --> 00:21:41,440
 and you say, oh, I'm going to apply this.

431
00:21:41,440 --> 00:21:45,480
 So in a sense, everybody's an individual,

432
00:21:45,480 --> 00:21:49,720
 and we don't have to think about the identities, in a sense.

433
00:21:49,720 --> 00:21:52,720
 The world is full of people, individual people,

434
00:21:52,720 --> 00:21:54,640
 with all their journeys.

435
00:21:54,640 --> 00:21:58,480
 But we're all human, so we don't think about that.

436
00:21:58,480 --> 00:22:02,520
 The problem here is that while the idea of being

437
00:22:02,520 --> 00:22:07,160
 seen as individuals with personal particularity

438
00:22:07,160 --> 00:22:16,080
 sounds great, it fails many minorities who are not white.

439
00:22:16,080 --> 00:22:18,280
 In that this kind of individualism

440
00:22:18,280 --> 00:22:23,840
 doesn't allow you to make sense of collective experiences

441
00:22:23,840 --> 00:22:25,880
 of culture or race.

442
00:22:25,880 --> 00:22:34,640
 Because of anti-Asian racism during COVID,

443
00:22:34,640 --> 00:22:36,520
 there's people all over the world,

444
00:22:36,520 --> 00:22:38,920
 actually, especially people who are living in predominantly

445
00:22:38,920 --> 00:22:42,240
 white countries, who had to wake up and realize, oh, I just

446
00:22:42,240 --> 00:22:45,000
 can't just blend in.

447
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:46,560
 We're Asian.

448
00:22:46,560 --> 00:22:49,120
 We can blend in if we can, but we can't,

449
00:22:49,120 --> 00:22:51,000
 because you stick out.

450
00:22:51,000 --> 00:22:53,160
 And so people have to think about that.

451
00:22:53,160 --> 00:22:55,320
 Well, how do you make sense of that when we're just

452
00:22:55,320 --> 00:22:58,400
 all individuals, because it's a collective experience?

453
00:22:58,400 --> 00:23:01,920
 So they would go to a white church or read Tim Keller,

454
00:23:01,920 --> 00:23:03,440
 and you can't talk about this.

455
00:23:03,440 --> 00:23:06,640
 You don't have language for this.

456
00:23:06,640 --> 00:23:11,120
 So you realize that whether it be a racial experience,

457
00:23:11,120 --> 00:23:12,320
 a cultural experience--

458
00:23:12,320 --> 00:23:13,200
 I'm Korean-American.

459
00:23:13,200 --> 00:23:14,640
 I grew up in Korea.

460
00:23:14,640 --> 00:23:16,520
 And I immigrated over.

461
00:23:16,520 --> 00:23:19,000
 My family immigrated over when I was 10,

462
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:21,360
 and I've lived there for decades.

463
00:23:21,360 --> 00:23:25,240
 And so I consider myself Asian-American as well

464
00:23:25,240 --> 00:23:27,240
 as Korean-American.

465
00:23:27,240 --> 00:23:29,120
 But that can't be really acknowledged,

466
00:23:29,120 --> 00:23:31,480
 because we're just all individuals.

467
00:23:31,480 --> 00:23:34,000
 So after a while, you feel like, this doesn't really help me.

468
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:36,200
 There's something missing.

469
00:23:36,200 --> 00:23:37,200
 It's helpful.

470
00:23:37,200 --> 00:23:39,480
 Of course, I still think Tim Keller

471
00:23:39,480 --> 00:23:42,120
 has been really influential in my life, personally even.

472
00:23:42,120 --> 00:23:44,160
 But there's something missing.

473
00:23:44,160 --> 00:23:45,360
 What is that something?

474
00:23:45,360 --> 00:23:49,080
 So people will say, unsatisfied, some Asian-Americans

475
00:23:49,080 --> 00:23:50,960
 say, I need better representation.

476
00:23:50,960 --> 00:23:53,000
 I need a way of being seen.

477
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:56,400
 I want to seek out this Asian-American identity

478
00:23:56,400 --> 00:24:00,560
 with its collective stories about cultural heritage

479
00:24:00,560 --> 00:24:03,680
 and migration experience and racial trauma.

480
00:24:03,680 --> 00:24:11,760
 So they run to Asian-American theology, right?

481
00:24:11,760 --> 00:24:16,120
 And what can go wrong?

482
00:24:16,120 --> 00:24:19,720
 What can go wrong by running to Asian-American theology?

483
00:24:19,720 --> 00:24:24,240
 And this has been my experience, in a sense, right?

484
00:24:24,240 --> 00:24:30,000
 And Asian-American theology says, oh, you know who you are.

485
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:34,040
 You are heir of this Confucian heritage.

486
00:24:34,040 --> 00:24:42,120
 While the white-dominant rubric is mostly individualistic,

487
00:24:42,120 --> 00:24:46,240
 blind to cultural and structural forces,

488
00:24:46,240 --> 00:24:49,400
 the Asian-American frame, and actually

489
00:24:49,400 --> 00:24:52,720
 a lot of other minority frames as well,

490
00:24:52,720 --> 00:24:57,400
 suffers from a different kind of a problem, right?

491
00:24:57,400 --> 00:25:03,760
 It's what I would call kind of a reductive or collectivist

492
00:25:03,760 --> 00:25:05,320
 essentialism.

493
00:25:05,320 --> 00:25:10,160
 It's a way of reducing people down, right?

494
00:25:10,160 --> 00:25:14,280
 So in a sense, you say, well, who are you really?

495
00:25:14,280 --> 00:25:16,800
 And then you get to kind of talk about your true identity,

496
00:25:16,800 --> 00:25:19,240
 in a sense.

497
00:25:19,240 --> 00:25:24,320
 Post-colonial theorist, Gayatri Spivak,

498
00:25:24,320 --> 00:25:27,760
 she talks about this idea of strategic essentialism,

499
00:25:27,760 --> 00:25:30,800
 that when you're trying to politically navigate, right,

500
00:25:30,800 --> 00:25:33,440
 to mobilize, you have to kind of talk about your core,

501
00:25:33,440 --> 00:25:35,280
 because you can't talk about everybody else.

502
00:25:35,280 --> 00:25:37,480
 You have to say, what do we share together?

503
00:25:37,480 --> 00:25:42,320
 You do it mostly for representation and activism.

504
00:25:42,320 --> 00:25:48,800
 And in a sense, we do this--

505
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:52,920
 we can use like an East versus West kind of Orientalism.

506
00:25:52,920 --> 00:25:54,080
 We can talk about--

507
00:25:54,080 --> 00:25:55,240
 or we can talk about--

508
00:25:55,240 --> 00:25:57,000
 when we talk about Asian-American theology

509
00:25:57,000 --> 00:25:59,680
 using the strategic essentialism,

510
00:25:59,680 --> 00:26:01,120
 it usually sounds like this.

511
00:26:01,120 --> 00:26:02,160
 You say, well, look--

512
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:04,080
 I mean, for Korean-Americans, they'll say, oh,

513
00:26:04,080 --> 00:26:06,520
 it's really Korean theology or Korean-American theology

514
00:26:06,520 --> 00:26:09,800
 is really all about Han.

515
00:26:09,800 --> 00:26:11,320
 You might have heard that, right?

516
00:26:11,320 --> 00:26:13,480
 It's really about Han.

517
00:26:13,480 --> 00:26:15,600
 Or maybe it's really--

518
00:26:15,600 --> 00:26:16,400
 maybe it's not Han.

519
00:26:16,400 --> 00:26:18,560
 Maybe it's Jeong.

520
00:26:18,560 --> 00:26:20,720
 Or maybe it's Yen-Yang.

521
00:26:20,720 --> 00:26:22,840
 Or maybe it's family.

522
00:26:22,840 --> 00:26:24,400
 Maybe it's collectivism.

523
00:26:24,400 --> 00:26:25,640
 Maybe it's marginality.

524
00:26:25,640 --> 00:26:27,040
 Maybe it's shame.

525
00:26:27,040 --> 00:26:28,080
 Maybe it's liminality.

526
00:26:28,080 --> 00:26:32,000
 Maybe it's the Confucian mindset.

527
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:36,160
 But if you don't fit neatly into those things,

528
00:26:36,160 --> 00:26:40,520
 and you feel like that doesn't really describe you that well,

529
00:26:40,520 --> 00:26:44,400
 then you feel like this is not your space either.

530
00:26:44,400 --> 00:26:49,920
 And even in the Asian-American community,

531
00:26:49,920 --> 00:26:51,960
 there are different kinds of Asian-Americans.

532
00:26:51,960 --> 00:26:55,840
 It's not like all of us are like, oh, we like Confucians.

533
00:26:55,840 --> 00:26:58,000
 There are people who are like, yeah, I don't like it,

534
00:26:58,000 --> 00:26:59,360
 but my parents is like this.

535
00:26:59,360 --> 00:27:00,600
 Other people are like, oh, no, my parents

536
00:27:00,600 --> 00:27:01,720
 are very progressive.

537
00:27:01,720 --> 00:27:03,800
 They never even thought this about.

538
00:27:03,800 --> 00:27:05,640
 My mom wasn't a Taiwan mom.

539
00:27:05,640 --> 00:27:07,200
 Just didn't really-- it wasn't something

540
00:27:07,200 --> 00:27:08,320
 that they thought about.

541
00:27:08,320 --> 00:27:09,760
 And actually, if you think that--

542
00:27:09,760 --> 00:27:10,840
 well, that's a stereotype, right?

543
00:27:10,840 --> 00:27:12,320
 The idea of a stereotype is the fact

544
00:27:12,320 --> 00:27:16,200
 that you say it's a reductive kind of way of talking

545
00:27:16,200 --> 00:27:17,640
 about people in general.

546
00:27:17,640 --> 00:27:20,560
 And stereotypes, as you know, is racist,

547
00:27:20,560 --> 00:27:23,560
 because it's suffocating after a while.

548
00:27:23,560 --> 00:27:24,760
 Is there truth to it?

549
00:27:24,760 --> 00:27:26,200
 Yes, there is.

550
00:27:26,200 --> 00:27:28,280
 But do you want to deal with stereotypes?

551
00:27:28,280 --> 00:27:30,720
 That's not very helpful.

552
00:27:30,720 --> 00:27:34,960
 This is what I call kind of a contextual paradox.

553
00:27:34,960 --> 00:27:38,120
 You read white theology, and you find that frustrating.

554
00:27:38,120 --> 00:27:40,600
 You read Asian or Asian-American theology,

555
00:27:40,600 --> 00:27:42,520
 and you find that very frustrating.

556
00:27:42,520 --> 00:27:45,600
 Here, you can be an individual.

557
00:27:45,600 --> 00:27:47,960
 But it doesn't really describe your experience.

558
00:27:47,960 --> 00:27:50,440
 You go over to Asian or Asian-American theology,

559
00:27:50,440 --> 00:27:52,000
 and you say, wait a minute.

560
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:53,920
 Now I'm in a straitjacket.

561
00:27:53,920 --> 00:27:56,320
 And I feel suffocated, because I don't

562
00:27:56,320 --> 00:28:01,520
 feel like my individual particular experience

563
00:28:01,520 --> 00:28:04,480
 and my particular features are really valued.

564
00:28:04,480 --> 00:28:05,760
 So what do I choose?

565
00:28:05,760 --> 00:28:08,600
 Should I choose where I can be myself?

566
00:28:08,600 --> 00:28:10,280
 Or should I choose a straitjacket,

567
00:28:10,280 --> 00:28:12,960
 where everybody just gets to be in a stereotype?

568
00:28:12,960 --> 00:28:17,600
 This is why I found Asian-American theology

569
00:28:17,600 --> 00:28:18,640
 frustrating.

570
00:28:18,640 --> 00:28:20,040
 I just didn't like it.

571
00:28:20,040 --> 00:28:21,740
 Like, I'm not a typical Korean-American.

572
00:28:21,740 --> 00:28:24,680
 I'm a typical Korean-American, whatever that might be.

573
00:28:24,680 --> 00:28:26,640
 What is that, right?

574
00:28:26,640 --> 00:28:30,720
 Whatever the stereotype of a racist thing.

575
00:28:30,720 --> 00:28:31,960
 I don't eat kimchi every day.

576
00:28:31,960 --> 00:28:33,520
 Whatever, right?

577
00:28:33,520 --> 00:28:34,280
 It's nonsense.

578
00:28:34,280 --> 00:28:36,680
 It's literally nonsense, right?

579
00:28:36,680 --> 00:28:38,440
 But that's basically what it sounded like.

580
00:28:38,440 --> 00:28:40,320
 So I said, well, this house is helpful.

581
00:28:40,320 --> 00:28:44,400
 I might as well just read Calvin at this point.

582
00:28:44,400 --> 00:28:49,280
 You find yourself in this crisis.

583
00:28:49,280 --> 00:28:53,040
 And I think the paradoxical intervention is the fact

584
00:28:53,040 --> 00:28:56,360
 that you want to define a context in a way,

585
00:28:56,360 --> 00:28:59,920
 but you don't want to do it in such a way that it's reductive.

586
00:28:59,920 --> 00:29:01,160
 There's room.

587
00:29:01,160 --> 00:29:03,600
 There's room to be, yeah, these are what matters,

588
00:29:03,600 --> 00:29:05,400
 but I'm not telling you who you are.

589
00:29:05,400 --> 00:29:09,240
 These are things that we have to kind of negotiate with, right?

590
00:29:09,240 --> 00:29:16,120
 So you want to describe a context or identity concretely.

591
00:29:16,120 --> 00:29:18,480
 But what you want to do is you want

592
00:29:18,480 --> 00:29:23,320
 to avoid essentialism, the stereotypical reduction, right?

593
00:29:23,320 --> 00:29:27,560
 Oh, you know, I heard Hong Kongers are all like this.

594
00:29:27,560 --> 00:29:30,560
 You know, there's some Chinese people over here.

595
00:29:30,560 --> 00:29:32,240
 Chinese, what?

596
00:29:32,240 --> 00:29:34,000
 Like, that's a stereotypical word, right?

597
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:35,960
 Just Chinese people?

598
00:29:35,960 --> 00:29:37,440
 What kind, right?

599
00:29:37,440 --> 00:29:39,760
 Because as you know, those Chinese people

600
00:29:39,760 --> 00:29:42,280
 and Singaporeans, apparently Hong Kongers

601
00:29:42,280 --> 00:29:45,560
 don't like that much from what I've heard, right?

602
00:29:45,560 --> 00:29:47,040
 They're very different.

603
00:29:47,040 --> 00:29:49,720
 What does that mean to understand where you are?

604
00:29:49,720 --> 00:29:54,000
 So you want to avoid this lazy, dull collectivism,

605
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:56,640
 this essentialism, because that's not going to help us.

606
00:29:56,640 --> 00:30:00,440
 You have to avoid this essentialism that

607
00:30:00,440 --> 00:30:07,000
 allows for diversity, dynamism, a way to have this flexibility.

608
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:11,880
 And in a sense, in terms of anthropology, what you find

609
00:30:11,880 --> 00:30:13,200
 is that--

610
00:30:13,200 --> 00:30:16,320
 Katherine Tanner has a book on the theology of culture.

611
00:30:16,320 --> 00:30:18,880
 And she talks about the difference between modern

612
00:30:18,880 --> 00:30:20,880
 perspective, modern anthropology,

613
00:30:20,880 --> 00:30:22,600
 and postmodern anthropology.

614
00:30:22,600 --> 00:30:24,160
 In a sense, earlier modern anthropology

615
00:30:24,160 --> 00:30:27,240
 was talking about the fact that culture is static.

616
00:30:27,240 --> 00:30:28,320
 It has its boundaries.

617
00:30:28,320 --> 00:30:29,520
 This is who we are.

618
00:30:29,520 --> 00:30:32,920
 And there's such thing as shame culture societies.

619
00:30:32,920 --> 00:30:34,800
 There's guilt culture societies.

620
00:30:34,800 --> 00:30:36,280
 Very distinct.

621
00:30:36,280 --> 00:30:38,680
 Which one are you?

622
00:30:38,680 --> 00:30:41,880
 And she says, this is actually not how culture is at all.

623
00:30:41,880 --> 00:30:44,840
 The postmodern development said, well, it

624
00:30:44,840 --> 00:30:47,360
 doesn't really work that way, right?

625
00:30:47,360 --> 00:30:49,080
 I mean, it's helpful in some degree.

626
00:30:49,080 --> 00:30:51,800
 But even as a model, it's too suffocating.

627
00:30:51,800 --> 00:30:54,840
 It doesn't really work.

628
00:30:54,840 --> 00:30:59,240
 Postmodern developments, why not rejecting the modern ideas?

629
00:30:59,240 --> 00:31:02,840
 Start thinking about historical process.

630
00:31:02,840 --> 00:31:05,400
 The culture is not something that's given,

631
00:31:05,400 --> 00:31:07,520
 something that's formed, something that's actually

632
00:31:07,520 --> 00:31:08,960
 finished.

633
00:31:08,960 --> 00:31:10,560
 But it's alive.

634
00:31:10,560 --> 00:31:13,600
 It's changing.

635
00:31:13,600 --> 00:31:17,040
 I'll tell you something interesting.

636
00:31:17,040 --> 00:31:19,600
 So I have a student--

637
00:31:19,600 --> 00:31:22,560
 it's not in my manuscript, but I'll tell you.

638
00:31:22,560 --> 00:31:24,960
 So I have a lot of Chinese-American students

639
00:31:24,960 --> 00:31:27,040
 who might be third generation, fourth generation,

640
00:31:27,040 --> 00:31:28,800
 or whatever.

641
00:31:28,800 --> 00:31:31,280
 And I had one student.

642
00:31:31,280 --> 00:31:33,480
 He went to visit--

643
00:31:33,480 --> 00:31:35,120
 he went to Shanghai.

644
00:31:35,120 --> 00:31:39,960
 He came back and said, professor, people in Shanghai

645
00:31:39,960 --> 00:31:44,120
 don't act like how they should.

646
00:31:44,120 --> 00:31:46,080
 And I said, how should they act?

647
00:31:46,080 --> 00:31:49,200
 Well, they don't act Chinese.

648
00:31:49,200 --> 00:31:50,680
 And I was like, what does that mean?

649
00:31:50,680 --> 00:31:52,240
 You know, like, well, my grandma said,

650
00:31:52,240 --> 00:31:54,000
 well, when did your grandma come?

651
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:57,240
 Like, 80-- well, that's--

652
00:31:57,240 --> 00:31:59,920
 China's moved on, right?

653
00:31:59,920 --> 00:32:03,240
 There's this problem of a time capsule.

654
00:32:03,240 --> 00:32:04,920
 And this is a very common thing.

655
00:32:04,920 --> 00:32:07,680
 When you immigrate over, you take whatever is there,

656
00:32:07,680 --> 00:32:10,520
 and you protect it, which is really bizarre.

657
00:32:10,520 --> 00:32:11,960
 Like, you know, you protect this thing.

658
00:32:11,960 --> 00:32:13,640
 The first generation is like, this is what it is.

659
00:32:13,640 --> 00:32:15,800
 And maybe later generation say, oh, you

660
00:32:15,800 --> 00:32:19,160
 should be more Chinese with this thing.

661
00:32:19,160 --> 00:32:22,000
 In the meantime, this is moving along, right?

662
00:32:22,000 --> 00:32:25,040
 China's-- it's gone, right?

663
00:32:25,040 --> 00:32:28,160
 Same thing with my parents when they visited Korea.

664
00:32:28,160 --> 00:32:30,040
 Like, you know, because it's been like 40 years

665
00:32:30,040 --> 00:32:31,440
 since we immigrated over.

666
00:32:31,440 --> 00:32:34,360
 My parents visited Korea, came back and said, oh,

667
00:32:34,360 --> 00:32:35,440
 my Korean name is Dongwoo.

668
00:32:35,440 --> 00:32:39,320
 It's like, Dongwoo, you are more Korean

669
00:32:39,320 --> 00:32:40,400
 than the Koreans in Korea.

670
00:32:40,400 --> 00:32:42,920
 [LAUGHTER]

671
00:32:42,920 --> 00:32:47,440
 And I looked at my parents and said, that is nonsense.

672
00:32:47,440 --> 00:32:51,080
 The word you're using for Korean is literally nonsense.

673
00:32:51,080 --> 00:32:52,840
 It doesn't help us, right?

674
00:32:52,840 --> 00:32:54,600
 And you've been telling me all this time,

675
00:32:54,600 --> 00:32:55,720
 I should be more Korean.

676
00:32:55,720 --> 00:32:59,080
 But apparently, this whole idea of Koreanness is nonsense,

677
00:32:59,080 --> 00:32:59,880
 right?

678
00:32:59,880 --> 00:33:00,880
 There's something there.

679
00:33:00,880 --> 00:33:01,840
 It's not total nonsense.

680
00:33:01,840 --> 00:33:04,480
 But it's actually dynamic, right?

681
00:33:04,480 --> 00:33:06,720
 That's the point, right?

682
00:33:06,720 --> 00:33:08,840
 It's being continually negotiated.

683
00:33:08,840 --> 00:33:09,720
 It's passed down.

684
00:33:09,720 --> 00:33:12,440
 But there's something here that's actually contradictions

685
00:33:12,440 --> 00:33:14,960
 and there are change, conflict, and there

686
00:33:14,960 --> 00:33:19,040
 are different people who like it, don't like it, right?

687
00:33:19,040 --> 00:33:25,040
 I mean, to some degree, how we think about Asianness

688
00:33:25,040 --> 00:33:26,720
 is kind of like this, right?

689
00:33:26,720 --> 00:33:28,320
 It's basically Hong Kong.

690
00:33:28,320 --> 00:33:30,000
 Are you confusion?

691
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:31,840
 Well, maybe, yes.

692
00:33:31,840 --> 00:33:34,720
 But if you said, theology should be done,

693
00:33:34,720 --> 00:33:36,800
 when we contextualize to Asian people,

694
00:33:36,800 --> 00:33:39,720
 we should have a confusion for theology,

695
00:33:39,720 --> 00:33:41,080
 would it work for Hong Kong?

696
00:33:41,080 --> 00:33:45,480
 It would not, because you are not like that, right?

697
00:33:45,480 --> 00:33:46,960
 It doesn't work for you.

698
00:33:46,960 --> 00:33:48,120
 So you look at that and say, well,

699
00:33:48,120 --> 00:33:51,760
 I might as well just read Calvin at this point, right?

700
00:33:51,760 --> 00:33:53,040
 Because it's too suffocating.

701
00:33:53,040 --> 00:33:55,400
 It's bad methodology.

702
00:33:55,400 --> 00:33:59,840
 There's something here, but it's bad methodology.

703
00:33:59,840 --> 00:34:02,000
 And just by saying, well, we're all just a big soup

704
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:04,040
 of everything, it doesn't really help you either,

705
00:34:04,040 --> 00:34:06,680
 because the soup still has different ingredients.

706
00:34:06,680 --> 00:34:08,960
 It's not like you just throw everything in soup

707
00:34:08,960 --> 00:34:10,680
 and it's delicious.

708
00:34:10,680 --> 00:34:13,520
 I mean, you have to figure out what's in there.

709
00:34:13,520 --> 00:34:15,880
 What I usually use is this.

710
00:34:15,880 --> 00:34:20,880
 So in this sense, I say, I think about this,

711
00:34:20,880 --> 00:34:25,160
 and I use a kind of a linguistic approach, right?

712
00:34:25,160 --> 00:34:27,120
 According to cognitive linguistics,

713
00:34:27,120 --> 00:34:33,120
 our experience is processed through language, okay?

714
00:34:33,120 --> 00:34:38,400
 And language, as you know, describes our experience.

715
00:34:38,400 --> 00:34:41,200
 It interprets our experience,

716
00:34:41,200 --> 00:34:45,800
 but it also constructs our experience.

717
00:34:45,800 --> 00:34:48,760
 And it's generative to think about the world

718
00:34:48,760 --> 00:34:49,720
 in different ways.

719
00:34:49,720 --> 00:34:52,160
 So keep that in mind.

720
00:34:52,160 --> 00:34:53,960
 I'm actually approaching this,

721
00:34:53,960 --> 00:34:57,200
 my idea of contextual kind of description,

722
00:34:57,200 --> 00:35:00,720
 as a linguistic approach, not language per se, right?

723
00:35:00,720 --> 00:35:03,120
 But this idea of a vocabulary.

724
00:35:03,120 --> 00:35:04,400
 What words do you use?

725
00:35:04,400 --> 00:35:05,680
 How do you talk about this?

726
00:35:05,680 --> 00:35:09,840
 And how do you talk about it in an expansive way, right?

727
00:35:09,840 --> 00:35:12,440
 Just not like a reductive way.

728
00:35:15,480 --> 00:35:18,440
 When I, let me tell you what I mean by expansive, okay?

729
00:35:18,440 --> 00:35:24,400
 I grew up telling my friends,

730
00:35:24,400 --> 00:35:27,040
 and all of our friends talk this way.

731
00:35:27,040 --> 00:35:32,040
 We would say, "Oh, that pastor, so Korean, ah.

732
00:35:32,040 --> 00:35:37,320
 "Oh, that pastor's so Americanized, good."

733
00:35:37,320 --> 00:35:38,400
 (audience laughing)

734
00:35:38,400 --> 00:35:40,120
 And my friend, who's actually, you know,

735
00:35:40,120 --> 00:35:41,800
 he's like third generation Chinese American,

736
00:35:41,800 --> 00:35:44,680
 he's older, he goes, "Oh yeah, I grew up with the same word.

737
00:35:44,680 --> 00:35:46,120
 "We call that Chinesey.

738
00:35:46,120 --> 00:35:49,320
 "Oh, my grandma, she smell like tiger balm

739
00:35:49,320 --> 00:35:53,800
 "and mushrooms and bitter melon, Chinesey, ah."

740
00:35:53,800 --> 00:35:54,840
 Right?

741
00:35:54,840 --> 00:35:57,040
 And I was like, "That's ridiculous.

742
00:35:57,040 --> 00:36:00,200
 "China is like this middle kingdom of 5,000 years.

743
00:36:00,200 --> 00:36:02,080
 "How do you use the word that reductively?

744
00:36:02,080 --> 00:36:04,600
 "It's ridiculous, are you five years old?"

745
00:36:04,600 --> 00:36:09,400
 That's how a lot of Asian Americans use the word Chinese.

746
00:36:09,400 --> 00:36:10,640
 They don't know anything.

747
00:36:12,280 --> 00:36:16,560
 It's like kindergarten level articulation, right?

748
00:36:16,560 --> 00:36:17,840
 That's what I mean by language.

749
00:36:17,840 --> 00:36:21,760
 You need something a lot more extensive, right?

750
00:36:21,760 --> 00:36:23,000
 Nobody says that's Chinese.

751
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:24,480
 I mean, people in China, they don't talk that way.

752
00:36:24,480 --> 00:36:26,040
 It's ridiculous.

753
00:36:26,040 --> 00:36:28,240
 But that's what's gonna happen

754
00:36:28,240 --> 00:36:29,520
 if you don't really have articulation.

755
00:36:29,520 --> 00:36:31,680
 Now, that's a particularly Asian American problem

756
00:36:31,680 --> 00:36:34,520
 because we get a purely white education.

757
00:36:34,520 --> 00:36:35,680
 That doesn't really help us.

758
00:36:35,680 --> 00:36:36,600
 I mean, it's better in Hong Kong

759
00:36:36,600 --> 00:36:38,040
 'cause you can learn about these things, right?

760
00:36:38,040 --> 00:36:40,000
 You can learn about, okay, this is basically

761
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:40,840
 what the history is.

762
00:36:40,840 --> 00:36:42,800
 You can learn about the complications

763
00:36:42,800 --> 00:36:44,200
 of what Confucius and Buddhism looks like.

764
00:36:44,200 --> 00:36:47,040
 It's not a fortune cookie, right?

765
00:36:47,040 --> 00:36:49,280
 Because that's what it is sometimes in the US.

766
00:36:49,280 --> 00:36:50,240
 You don't really understand.

767
00:36:50,240 --> 00:36:51,960
 It's like, oh, I read an article.

768
00:36:51,960 --> 00:36:52,840
 I realize it's bad.

769
00:36:52,840 --> 00:36:55,640
 I'm like, you read one article of a tradition

770
00:36:55,640 --> 00:36:58,480
 over 2,000 years old and you think the whole thing's bad.

771
00:36:58,480 --> 00:37:02,560
 That's how people talk, right?

772
00:37:02,560 --> 00:37:04,920
 That's how people talk, okay.

773
00:37:04,920 --> 00:37:08,800
 So the idea is the fact that we are like fish in water.

774
00:37:08,800 --> 00:37:10,320
 That's my illustration.

775
00:37:10,320 --> 00:37:15,120
 Imagine the fact that we're fish living in murky water.

776
00:37:15,120 --> 00:37:20,000
 And I really don't know what the Chinese proverb,

777
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:24,240
 but I've read that the Chinese proverb says,

778
00:37:24,240 --> 00:37:29,040
 if you want to know what water is, you don't ask a fish.

779
00:37:29,040 --> 00:37:32,680
 'Cause it's very difficult when you're swimming

780
00:37:32,680 --> 00:37:35,320
 in something to know what that is.

781
00:37:35,320 --> 00:37:37,320
 And you have to tell me 'cause I'm gonna write it down.

782
00:37:39,120 --> 00:37:43,480
 If your whole existence is in this aquatic world,

783
00:37:43,480 --> 00:37:47,040
 born, eating, swimming, mating, dying,

784
00:37:47,040 --> 00:37:49,440
 and you're breathing in, it becomes part of who you are.

785
00:37:49,440 --> 00:37:51,520
 It's very difficult to know what that is,

786
00:37:51,520 --> 00:37:52,840
 but it is definitely there.

787
00:37:52,840 --> 00:37:55,480
 There is something there, right?

788
00:37:55,480 --> 00:37:56,920
 Now, a lot of you, you might be like,

789
00:37:56,920 --> 00:38:00,800
 oh, I've been Christian for generations.

790
00:38:00,800 --> 00:38:03,600
 But do you not think that Buddhism is still in you?

791
00:38:03,600 --> 00:38:06,680
 I'm not trying to say you should be Buddhist.

792
00:38:06,680 --> 00:38:08,440
 I'm just saying it's in you.

793
00:38:08,440 --> 00:38:10,520
 Like some of the food you eat, it's just vegetarian.

794
00:38:10,520 --> 00:38:13,760
 It's those glutens, which I love.

795
00:38:13,760 --> 00:38:16,720
 I mean, it's literally you're eating Buddhism, right?

796
00:38:16,720 --> 00:38:18,840
 There's something about that.

797
00:38:18,840 --> 00:38:21,680
 So it's in you, even though you're not trying to own it.

