 I mean, you can think of it as like an analogy,

1056
00:49:48,400 --> 00:49:49,920
 but that's all you can do.

1057
00:49:49,920 --> 00:49:51,200
 Theologically, properly speaking,

1058
00:49:51,200 --> 00:49:53,480
 there's no multiple incarnations.

1059
00:49:53,480 --> 00:49:56,760
 Jesus right now has like this Jewish body.

1060
00:49:58,200 --> 00:50:00,600
 And even though I know people like to have

1061
00:50:00,600 --> 00:50:02,240
 like an Asian picture of Jesus,

1062
00:50:02,240 --> 00:50:04,360
 Jesus never became Asian.

1063
00:50:04,360 --> 00:50:06,000
 Jesus never became white or black.

1064
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:08,120
 Jesus is actually a Jewish man forever,

1065
00:50:08,120 --> 00:50:10,800
 and that connection to Israel actually matters.

1066
00:50:10,800 --> 00:50:12,040
 Like biblically speaking, right?

1067
00:50:12,040 --> 00:50:15,560
 You can't just exchange Old Testament for sutras.

1068
00:50:15,560 --> 00:50:17,800
 It doesn't work that way, right?

1069
00:50:17,800 --> 00:50:23,400
 Given this, I think how sometimes it works

1070
00:50:23,400 --> 00:50:27,600
 is the fact that there's this eternal Word

1071
00:50:27,600 --> 00:50:29,520
 that becomes flesh.

1072
00:50:29,520 --> 00:50:31,280
 And sometimes, if you believe in this thing,

1073
00:50:31,280 --> 00:50:35,120
 it almost seems as though there's actually this pure gospel

1074
00:50:35,120 --> 00:50:38,760
 that becomes contextualized in different contexts.

1075
00:50:38,760 --> 00:50:41,800
 And I think this is kind of problematic

1076
00:50:41,800 --> 00:50:43,640
 because often missionaries are like,

1077
00:50:43,640 --> 00:50:48,640
 I bring the eternal Word to this pagan land, right?

1078
00:50:48,640 --> 00:50:52,800
 And I'm like, well, does it work that way, though?

1079
00:50:52,800 --> 00:50:54,680
 There's something wrong here.

1080
00:50:54,680 --> 00:50:55,840
 I mean, it's helpful, right?

1081
00:50:55,840 --> 00:50:58,080
 The idea of becoming incarnate is really, really,

1082
00:50:58,080 --> 00:51:01,360
 really, really powerful, and it's really, really important.

1083
00:51:01,360 --> 00:51:03,360
 But that as the only metaphor

1084
00:51:03,360 --> 00:51:05,480
 seems to be kind of problematic.

1085
00:51:05,480 --> 00:51:07,080
 I'm not sure if it really works.

1086
00:51:07,080 --> 00:51:12,160
 In Asian American context, I think,

1087
00:51:12,160 --> 00:51:16,320
 I think sometimes our experience in bodies

1088
00:51:16,320 --> 00:51:19,640
 ends up just being like a kernel and not the real thing.

1089
00:51:19,640 --> 00:51:21,840
 Like the kernel is this universal thing, in a sense.

1090
00:51:21,840 --> 00:51:23,800
 So what's the other, right?

1091
00:51:24,760 --> 00:51:28,200
 There are other, my colleague, Amos Young,

1092
00:51:28,200 --> 00:51:30,520
 who's a Pentecostal theologian, talks about this thing.

1093
00:51:30,520 --> 00:51:32,960
 He talks about this idea, the fact that,

1094
00:51:32,960 --> 00:51:37,960
 you know, the idea of spirit being poured on our flesh.

1095
00:51:37,960 --> 00:51:43,400
 And I think, as an Asian American,

1096
00:51:43,400 --> 00:51:45,120
 I see this thing and I say, well,

1097
00:51:45,120 --> 00:51:49,680
 it talks about languages, and it talks about pluralism.

1098
00:51:49,680 --> 00:51:53,440
 But I think, I'm thinking about, okay,

1099
00:51:53,440 --> 00:51:56,320
 cultural, linguistic, yes, but Asian American identity

1100
00:51:56,320 --> 00:51:57,800
 is a racial identity.

1101
00:51:57,800 --> 00:51:59,200
 Like it's kind of a weird thing.

1102
00:51:59,200 --> 00:52:00,120
 How does that cover it?

1103
00:52:00,120 --> 00:52:02,880
 'Cause we're talking about languages here, right?

1104
00:52:02,880 --> 00:52:05,760
 So it's helpful, but there's something else missing.

1105
00:52:05,760 --> 00:52:11,640
 What I propose is this idea of a covenantal.

1106
00:52:11,640 --> 00:52:15,920
 Here's what I mean.

1107
00:52:15,920 --> 00:52:16,960
 The example is this.

1108
00:52:16,960 --> 00:52:20,840
 God fundamentally is a God

1109
00:52:20,840 --> 00:52:23,720
 who actually interacts with us back and forth.

1110
00:52:23,720 --> 00:52:26,360
 And who you are matters to God

1111
00:52:26,360 --> 00:52:28,760
 as much as us mattering to God,

1112
00:52:28,760 --> 00:52:31,640
 which is really strange, but this is how the Bible works.

1113
00:52:31,640 --> 00:52:33,960
 God wants an I and thou,

1114
00:52:33,960 --> 00:52:35,520
 in terms of how Buber would talk about it,

1115
00:52:35,520 --> 00:52:38,080
 you know, German, a Jewish philosopher, Martin Buber,

1116
00:52:38,080 --> 00:52:40,280
 would say, God wants an I and thou relationship.

1117
00:52:40,280 --> 00:52:41,360
 As opposed to what?

1118
00:52:41,360 --> 00:52:42,720
 Well, I and I.

1119
00:52:42,720 --> 00:52:43,640
 Like God just says, well,

1120
00:52:43,640 --> 00:52:45,560
 I'm the only one that's important.

1121
00:52:45,560 --> 00:52:48,680
 Biblically, even though sometimes it sounds very spiritual,

1122
00:52:48,680 --> 00:52:49,880
 that's not really true.

1123
00:52:50,880 --> 00:52:53,640
 God says, oh, who you are actually matters.

1124
00:52:53,640 --> 00:52:57,080
 And you, biblically, can argue with God,

1125
00:52:57,080 --> 00:52:59,040
 you can wrestle with God.

1126
00:52:59,040 --> 00:53:00,920
 It's all part of biblical tradition

1127
00:53:00,920 --> 00:53:03,640
 because where you are and what you experience

1128
00:53:03,640 --> 00:53:06,400
 matters to God, right?

1129
00:53:06,400 --> 00:53:10,760
 It's not like a I and it, we're not just an object.

1130
00:53:10,760 --> 00:53:13,000
 We just don't follow what God says

1131
00:53:13,000 --> 00:53:13,920
 'cause there will be angels.

1132
00:53:13,920 --> 00:53:15,320
 Angels don't protest at all.

1133
00:53:15,320 --> 00:53:18,240
 Angels never fight with God.

1134
00:53:18,240 --> 00:53:21,920
 But people of God, because they're called Israel,

1135
00:53:21,920 --> 00:53:23,600
 what does Israel mean, right?

1136
00:53:23,600 --> 00:53:24,680
 People wrestle with God.

1137
00:53:24,680 --> 00:53:26,960
 And I always say, well, why would you name your people

1138
00:53:26,960 --> 00:53:28,320
 like wrestlers with God?

1139
00:53:28,320 --> 00:53:30,080
 Why don't you say people who submit,

1140
00:53:30,080 --> 00:53:31,960
 you know, be nice, good kids, right?

1141
00:53:31,960 --> 00:53:34,800
 No, people who wrestle and engage with God.

1142
00:53:34,800 --> 00:53:35,960
 That actually matters.

1143
00:53:35,960 --> 00:53:38,120
 Who you are matters.

1144
00:53:38,120 --> 00:53:40,440
 So when you see the Bible, you realize,

1145
00:53:40,440 --> 00:53:44,520
 when we have Moses, God has a very particular call

1146
00:53:44,520 --> 00:53:46,400
 for Moses in the Egyptian empire.

1147
00:53:46,400 --> 00:53:49,840
 God has a particular call for Daniel in the Egyptian empire,

1148
00:53:49,840 --> 00:53:52,880
 you know, Babylonian empire, or Esther in Persian empire,

1149
00:53:52,880 --> 00:53:55,400
 or Mary and Paul in the Roman empire.

1150
00:53:55,400 --> 00:53:59,280
 And these calls are not interchangeable, right?

1151
00:53:59,280 --> 00:54:00,280
 They're not interchangeable.

1152
00:54:00,280 --> 00:54:01,880
 They're just for them.

1153
00:54:01,880 --> 00:54:06,880
 Or in this sense, we have four gospel writers,

1154
00:54:06,880 --> 00:54:09,880
 Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John.

1155
00:54:09,880 --> 00:54:11,520
 They're all men, they're all Jews,

1156
00:54:11,520 --> 00:54:13,440
 but they're very different.

1157
00:54:15,200 --> 00:54:19,320
 Who they are matters, right?

1158
00:54:19,320 --> 00:54:21,960
 In this sense, this is, for me,

1159
00:54:21,960 --> 00:54:24,520
 the strongest argument for contextuality.

1160
00:54:24,520 --> 00:54:27,000
 That it's not just the fact

1161
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:28,880
 that God's just telling you something.

1162
00:54:28,880 --> 00:54:30,880
 God says, oh, I see you.

1163
00:54:30,880 --> 00:54:32,640
 And who you are matters to me,

1164
00:54:32,640 --> 00:54:34,600
 so I would tell you something different

1165
00:54:34,600 --> 00:54:39,040
 than what I would tell President Bernard, right?

1166
00:54:39,040 --> 00:54:41,600
 Like, you know, he was like, oh no, that's your call.

1167
00:54:41,600 --> 00:54:44,360
 This call is not your call, right?

1168
00:54:44,360 --> 00:54:47,760
 And because your family and your background's different,

1169
00:54:47,760 --> 00:54:49,200
 I'm gonna minister this way,

1170
00:54:49,200 --> 00:54:51,000
 which is actually just a good parent.

1171
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:52,320
 I have three daughters.

1172
00:54:52,320 --> 00:54:53,760
 I do not tell them the same thing,

1173
00:54:53,760 --> 00:54:55,760
 because you literally can't.

1174
00:54:55,760 --> 00:54:56,840
 They're different ages,

1175
00:54:56,840 --> 00:54:59,160
 and you have to love them differently.

1176
00:54:59,160 --> 00:55:01,560
 The only way you can love them fairly

1177
00:55:01,560 --> 00:55:03,560
 is to treat them differently.

1178
00:55:03,560 --> 00:55:05,480
 You know what I'm saying, right?

1179
00:55:05,480 --> 00:55:07,880
 The only way to be completely fair

1180
00:55:07,880 --> 00:55:09,800
 is to see who they are,

1181
00:55:09,800 --> 00:55:11,600
 and to say, well, it's gonna be slightly different,

1182
00:55:11,600 --> 00:55:12,960
 because if I talk the same way

1183
00:55:12,960 --> 00:55:16,320
 as I talk to my first kid to a second kid,

1184
00:55:16,320 --> 00:55:18,600
 she would just get crushed.

1185
00:55:18,600 --> 00:55:19,440
 I cannot do that.

1186
00:55:19,440 --> 00:55:20,720
 It does not work that way.

1187
00:55:20,720 --> 00:55:23,120
 That's what God's doing.

1188
00:55:23,120 --> 00:55:25,040
 That's contextuality.

1189
00:55:25,040 --> 00:55:28,040
 God is saying, you matter, your background matter,

1190
00:55:28,040 --> 00:55:29,920
 your political background matters,

1191
00:55:29,920 --> 00:55:32,440
 your family background matters, all that,

1192
00:55:32,440 --> 00:55:34,760
 and I'm interacting with you back and forth.

1193
00:55:34,760 --> 00:55:40,160
 That's the basis of contextuality, what God is like, right?

1194
00:55:41,160 --> 00:55:42,760
 In wrapping this up,

1195
00:55:42,760 --> 00:55:46,040
 I think the dangers of contextuality.

1196
00:55:46,040 --> 00:55:49,560
 This is a golden calf, okay?

1197
00:55:49,560 --> 00:55:51,360
 People always ask me, every question,

1198
00:55:51,360 --> 00:55:52,400
 like whenever I lecture on this,

1199
00:55:52,400 --> 00:55:54,760
 people always say, well, a professor

1200
00:55:54,760 --> 00:55:59,480
 isn't dealing with context dangerous?

1201
00:55:59,480 --> 00:56:04,440
 And I tell them, yes, it is, extremely.

1202
00:56:04,440 --> 00:56:07,720
 It's extremely dangerous.

1203
00:56:07,720 --> 00:56:08,560
 Can it be correct?

1204
00:56:08,560 --> 00:56:09,720
 It's extremely dangerous.

1205
00:56:09,720 --> 00:56:10,720
 Can it be corrupted?

1206
00:56:10,720 --> 00:56:11,760
 Oh, absolutely.

1207
00:56:11,760 --> 00:56:14,520
 If you're gonna start dealing with confusion or Buddhism,

1208
00:56:14,520 --> 00:56:17,520
 I mean, that's all dangerous, dangerous, dangerous.

1209
00:56:17,520 --> 00:56:20,640
 Syncretism, you know, can be like, you know,

1210
00:56:20,640 --> 00:56:22,240
 if you're gonna deal with political stuff,

1211
00:56:22,240 --> 00:56:26,600
 political, ideological takeover, you know, co-option,

1212
00:56:26,600 --> 00:56:29,320
 Babylonian captivity of every sort.

1213
00:56:29,320 --> 00:56:32,360
 It's extremely dangerous, right?

1214
00:56:32,360 --> 00:56:37,280
 Yeah, it's dangerous.

1215
00:56:38,280 --> 00:56:40,640
 But what is our option?

1216
00:56:40,640 --> 00:56:43,400
 What is our option?

1217
00:56:43,400 --> 00:56:48,200
 There's this idea, this is Geneva, okay?

1218
00:56:48,200 --> 00:56:50,160
 Now I'll describe it a little bit.

1219
00:56:50,160 --> 00:56:53,680
 This is a concept called ex-nomination

1220
00:56:53,680 --> 00:56:58,000
 by this French post-structuralist philosopher,

1221
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:02,120
 Roland Barthes, he talks about this idea of ex-nomination.

1222
00:57:02,120 --> 00:57:03,520
 Like what I said before, the very big,

1223
00:57:03,520 --> 00:57:05,120
 earlier on, beginning of the lecture,

1224
00:57:05,120 --> 00:57:07,680
 that sometimes people are contextual,

1225
00:57:07,680 --> 00:57:11,000
 but you don't know they are, right?

1226
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:14,560
 So what I'm saying is this contextual thing

1227
00:57:14,560 --> 00:57:18,280
 has already happened, right?

1228
00:57:18,280 --> 00:57:20,720
 Like in the US, there are people who are like,

1229
00:57:20,720 --> 00:57:22,560
 well, I don't believe in contextual anything,

1230
00:57:22,560 --> 00:57:24,440
 I just need my Bible and my gun.

1231
00:57:24,440 --> 00:57:28,440
 I'm like, nobody in the world thinks like you.

1232
00:57:28,440 --> 00:57:30,720
 The Bible and the gun idea is your idea,

1233
00:57:30,720 --> 00:57:32,160
 it's a contextual idea.

1234
00:57:32,160 --> 00:57:35,800
 That is a bizarre idea and a heretical idea.

1235
00:57:35,800 --> 00:57:37,680
 But they're like, well, this is what the Bible,

1236
00:57:37,680 --> 00:57:39,880
 but where, where are the verse, right?

1237
00:57:39,880 --> 00:57:41,240
 They don't think about the context,

1238
00:57:41,240 --> 00:57:43,720
 but the context has already happened.

1239
00:57:43,720 --> 00:57:45,240
 You don't have a choice.

1240
00:57:45,240 --> 00:57:46,400
 Is the contextual dangerous?

1241
00:57:46,400 --> 00:57:47,960
 Of course.

1242
00:57:47,960 --> 00:57:52,640
 If you don't wanna do it, it's still dangerous, right?

1243
00:57:52,640 --> 00:57:55,560
 So what are you gonna do, copy Reform theology and worship?

1244
00:57:55,560 --> 00:57:57,800
 This is, okay, they have this monument

1245
00:57:57,800 --> 00:57:59,920
 called the International Monument of the Reformation

1246
00:57:59,920 --> 00:58:01,560
 in Geneva, Switzerland.

1247
00:58:01,560 --> 00:58:06,120
 This is William Farrell, John Calvin, Beza, and John Knox.

1248
00:58:06,120 --> 00:58:09,040
 Five meters long.

1249
00:58:09,040 --> 00:58:12,120
 Five meters long, right?

1250
00:58:12,120 --> 00:58:15,520
 I mean, you're worshiping these people.

1251
00:58:15,520 --> 00:58:17,560
 You think, I know it's uncontextualized and hasn't happened,

1252
00:58:17,560 --> 00:58:20,040
 it's already happened, people.

1253
00:58:20,040 --> 00:58:22,000
 If you don't think about it explicitly,

1254
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:23,200
 it's already happened.

1255
00:58:23,200 --> 00:58:25,600
 You have to see the fact

1256
00:58:25,600 --> 00:58:27,600
 that you were already swimming in water.

1257
00:58:27,600 --> 00:58:30,000
 That's my point.

1258
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:31,080
 Is it dangerous?

1259
00:58:31,080 --> 00:58:32,560
 Absolutely.

1260
00:58:32,560 --> 00:58:34,360
 Is it dangerous if you don't do it?

1261
00:58:34,360 --> 00:58:35,640
 We're already in danger.

1262
00:58:35,640 --> 00:58:41,080
 Your gospel already has already been corrupted

1263
00:58:41,080 --> 00:58:46,080
 by Buddhism and Confucianism and capitalism.

1264
00:58:46,080 --> 00:58:48,160
 'Cause you know, it's Hong Kong.

1265
00:58:48,160 --> 00:58:49,920
 It's already happened.

1266
00:58:49,920 --> 00:58:52,000
 If you don't think about it, you don't have a choice.

1267
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:54,200
 You already have a corrupted gospel.

1268
00:58:54,200 --> 00:58:57,000
 I mean, I'm American, you know, we have our problems.

1269
00:58:58,080 --> 00:59:01,760
 Like, I left US on Sunday night,

1270
00:59:01,760 --> 00:59:03,160
 and then 'cause of the flight,

1271
00:59:03,160 --> 00:59:04,960
 there was no Monday, Monday disappeared.

1272
00:59:04,960 --> 00:59:06,400
 Monday was inauguration.

1273
00:59:06,400 --> 00:59:07,800
 (audience laughing)

1274
00:59:07,800 --> 00:59:09,640
 And then I landed on Tuesday.

1275
00:59:09,640 --> 00:59:12,040
 So what's weird is that I'm gonna land

1276
00:59:12,040 --> 00:59:14,080
 in a different country than I left,

1277
00:59:14,080 --> 00:59:15,240
 if you know what I mean.

1278
00:59:15,240 --> 00:59:17,240
 I'll just leave it at that.

1279
00:59:17,240 --> 00:59:19,280
 I'll end this with this final thought.

1280
00:59:19,280 --> 00:59:23,960
 The reason, one of the reasons

1281
00:59:23,960 --> 00:59:25,400
 why I like the reform tradition

1282
00:59:25,400 --> 00:59:27,400
 is because it's so self-critical.

1283
00:59:28,400 --> 00:59:29,520
 Right?

1284
00:59:29,520 --> 00:59:30,680
 It's self-critical.

1285
00:59:30,680 --> 00:59:33,520
 The whole idea is you have to keep on critiquing yourself.

1286
00:59:33,520 --> 00:59:34,360
 Right?

1287
00:59:34,360 --> 00:59:38,760
 This is a kind of a reformed kind of a model, right?

1288
00:59:38,760 --> 00:59:41,800
 Ecclesia Riformata, like church that's reformed,

1289
00:59:41,800 --> 00:59:43,640
 is Semper Riformata, right?

1290
00:59:43,640 --> 00:59:48,000
 Continue reforming, Secunda Verdi, by the word of God.

1291
00:59:48,000 --> 00:59:49,520
 We're just gonna wrestle with God.

1292
00:59:49,520 --> 00:59:52,360
 There is no place that's safe.

1293
00:59:52,360 --> 00:59:56,040
 We only are safe wrestling with God.

1294
00:59:57,040 --> 00:59:59,400
 That's the choice we have.

1295
00:59:59,400 --> 01:00:05,040
 But we have to do it well, and not the Chinesey,

1296
01:00:05,040 --> 01:00:07,200
 because that's not gonna help anybody.

1297
01:00:07,200 --> 01:00:08,760
 And we have to know the fact that it's rooted

1298
01:00:08,760 --> 01:00:12,440
 in the very heart of what God is like.

1299
01:00:12,440 --> 01:00:16,320
 And then we must continue to wrestle with God.

1300
01:00:16,320 --> 01:00:19,400
 And that's our call for us.

1301
01:00:19,400 --> 01:00:20,800
 Thank you.

1302
01:00:20,800 --> 01:00:23,960
 (audience applauding)

1303
01:00:24,920 --> 01:00:27,520
 (upbeat music)

1304
01:00:27,520 --> 01:00:30,120
 (upbeat music)

1305
01:00:30,120 --> 01:00:32,700
 (upbeat music)

1306
01:00:32,700 --> 01:00:35,280
 (upbeat music)

